SIMPLE: florid
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Florid
<hw>Flor"id</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>floridus</ets>, fr. <ets>flos</ets>, <ets>floris</ets>, flower. See
<er>Flower</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Covered with flowers; abounding
in flowers; flowery.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fruit from a pleasant and <qex>florid</qex> tree.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Bright in color; flushed with red; of a lively
reddish color; <as>as, a <ex>florid</ex> countenance</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Embellished with flowers of rhetoric; enriched to
excess with figures; excessively ornate; <as>as, a <ex>florid</ex>
style; <ex>florid</ex> eloquence.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Flowery; ornamental; running in
rapid melodic figures, divisions, or passages, as in variations; full of
fioriture or little ornamentations.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Florida bean</ent>⟦br⟧
